Asymmetric encryption is when the security key used to encrypt data is different from the key
used to decrypt it. If it can work successfully, there are significant benefits to be gained, as it
means two parties wanting to communicate in encrypted form do not have to meet privately to
exchange an agreed-upon encryption key, as is required for symmetric encryption. Instead, the
encryption key can be published publicly, and any person wishing to send a message can use it
to encrypt the data, so that only the recipient and key-holder can decrypt it to read.
For example: If Alice wants to send a secure message to Bob, she encrypts it using Bob’s public
key. Only Bob can decrypt this message with his private key.
